contract, it contracted

00:52:01.630 --> 00:52:04.860
with existing scientific
organizations at universities,

00:52:04.860 --> 00:52:06.670
so that they didn't
move the scientists

00:52:06.670 --> 00:52:09.300
into the War Department
or the Navy Department.

00:52:09.300 --> 00:52:10.940
They left them at
their universities.

00:52:10.940 --> 00:52:15.440
They created spaces for them
to work at their universities,

00:52:15.440 --> 00:52:18.640
and therefore, they
didn't disrupt the programs

00:52:18.640 --> 00:52:20.170
that were ongoing.

00:52:20.170 --> 00:52:21.470
So I think that contributed,
too.

00:52:21.470 --> 00:52:25.720
And so I think you need a
centralized authority to kind

00:52:25.720 --> 00:52:27.520
of get a handle on that.

00:52:27.520 --> 00:52:29.830
I don't know if that's possible.

00:52:29.830 --> 00:52:33.780
And a minimal disruption
to the existing status

00:52:33.780 --> 00:52:37.660
of the research environment
that's ongoing.

00:52:37.660 --> 00:52:39.970
And over here?

00:52:42.760 --> 00:52:45.800
&gt;&gt; Yes. Mark Wilson has written

00:52:45.800 --> 00:52:49.570
about the rather
extensive lobbying that went

00:52:49.570 --> 00:52:53.760
on before the war and at the
start of the war to make sure

00:52:53.760 --> 00:52:56.260
that defense production
was concentrated

00:52:56.260 --> 00:52:59.900
in the private sector rather
than the public sector.

00:52:59.900 --> 00:53:03.450
And one consequence of this was
that we had a lot of conversion

00:53:03.450 --> 00:53:07.470
of existing industrial plants
for defense production rather

00:53:07.470 --> 00:53:10.730
than construction of new
perhaps government-owned plants

00:53:10.730 --> 00:53:13.930
for defense production
or so is his argument.

00:53:13.930 --> 00:53:19.930
How does the research story
that you're telling relate

00:53:19.930 --> 00:53:24.290
to this effort to make sure
that what was produced resulting

00:53:24.290 --> 00:53:27.980
from this research was
predominantly produced

00:53:27.980 --> 00:53:29.530
in the private sector?

00:53:29.530 --> 00:53:31.470
&gt;&gt; Daniel Else: First of all,
I want to take a little bit

00:53:31.470 --> 00:53:37.090
of issue with the idea that
the government didn't build a

00:53:37.090 --> 00:53:43.240
massive industrial base
specifically for the war effort.

00:53:43.240 --> 00:53:45.650
They did. In fact, in fact,

00:53:45.650 --> 00:53:49.100
there was something called
the Defense Plant Corporation

00:53:49.100 --> 00:53:53.780
that was created in the early
1940s to do exactly that.

00:53:53.780 --> 00:53:56.320
They would build a
facility, they would build,

00:53:56.320 --> 00:53:59.310
they would stock it with
all the necessary equipment,

00:53:59.310 --> 00:54:01.450
and then they would
hire a private industry

00:54:01.450 --> 00:54:02.800
to come in and staff it.

00:54:02.800 --> 00:54:04.450
That's where you got
the defense plants.

00:54:04.450 --> 00:54:06.250
That's where you got
the defense workers

00:54:06.250 --> 00:54:07.730
who were not federal employees;

00:54:07.730 --> 00:54:10.110
they were private
corporation employees.

00:54:10.110 --> 00:54:13.300
But the liability for
the physical plant lay

00:54:13.300 --> 00:54:15.850
with the government,
because they owned the place.

00:54:15.850 --> 00:54:18.700
Something like, something
called Plant 42 out in Palmdale,

00:54:18.700 --> 00:54:22.820
California, which is, which
was operated essentially

00:54:22.820 --> 00:54:25.240
by Lockheed Martin,
the Skunk Works,

00:54:25.240 --> 00:54:28.460
that was a federally
funded, federally built plant

00:54:28.460 --> 00:54:34.040
in the 1940s that was operated
by a contractor over the years.

00:54:34.040 --> 00:54:38.980
So the idea that -- well,

00:54:38.980 --> 00:54:43.910
the reason for that lobbying
effort was, after World War I,

00:54:43.910 --> 00:54:47.380
the War and Navy Departments
cancelled outstanding

00:54:47.380 --> 00:54:48.680
war contracts.

00:54:48.680 --> 00:54:50.250
The armistice took
everybody by surprise.

00:54:50.250 --> 00:54:52.230
We were just gearing up,
there were massive numbers

00:54:52.230 --> 00:54:54.730
of contracts out there, civilian
corporations had converted

00:54:54.730 --> 00:54:56.200
over to war production, and all

00:54:56.200 --> 00:54:58.100
of a sudden, the
lights went out.

00:54:58.100 --> 00:55:00.280
And there were lawsuits
for the liability

00:55:00.280 --> 00:55:01.580
of those cancelled contracts

00:55:01.580 --> 00:55:03.930
that extended well
into World War II.

00:55:03.930 --> 00:55:06.150
So in order to avoid that,

00:55:06.150 --> 00:55:10.520
we had the defense plant
corporation product,

00:55:10.520 --> 00:55:14.930
that scheme of approaching
industrial production.

